href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
href="marcelofiore.xml"
type="local"
addr="marcelofiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:link
href="jms-00KF.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KF">function</fr:link> <fr:tex>f \colon  A  \to  B</fr:tex> is said to be <fr:em><fr:strong>bijective</fr:strong></fr:em> or <fr:em><fr:strong>bijection</fr:strong></fr:em> whenever there exists a (necessarily unique) function <fr:tex>g \colon  B \to  A</fr:tex> (referred to as the <fr:em><fr:strong>inverse</fr:strong></fr:em> of <fr:tex>f</fr:tex>) that is simultaneously a <fr:link
href="jms-00KS.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KS">retraction</fr:link> and a <fr:link
href="jms-00KS.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KS">section</fr:link> of <fr:tex>f \colon  A  \to  B</fr:tex> in the sense that <fr:tex>g \circ  f= \mathsf {id}_{ A }</fr:tex> and <fr:tex>f \circ  g =  \mathsf {id}_{ B }</fr:tex>.</fr:p><fr:p>We will often write <fr:tex>f ^{-1} \colon  B \to  A</fr:tex> for the inverse to a bijection <fr:tex>f \colon  A  \to  B</fr:tex>.</fr:p>
 
   
   <fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="false"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2315</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Proof</fr:taxon><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>23</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors><fr:parent>jms-00KR</fr:parent></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter>
 <fr:p>To see that <fr:tex>g \colon  B \to  A</fr:tex> is unique, we fix any other <fr:tex>g'</fr:tex> that is simultaneously a <fr:link
href="jms-00KS.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KS">retraction</fr:link> and a <fr:link
href="jms-00KS.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KS">section</fr:link> of <fr:tex>f</fr:tex> and show that <fr:tex>g=g'</fr:tex>:</fr:p>
 <fr:tex
display="block">    \begin {aligned}     g &amp;=  \mathsf {id}_{ A } \circ  g \\      &amp;=  { \mathopen {} \left ( g' \circ  f \right ) \mathclose {}}   \circ  g \\      &amp;= g' \circ { \mathopen {} \left ( f \circ  g \right ) \mathclose {}} \\      &amp;= g' \circ \mathsf {id}_{ B } \\      &amp;= g'    \end {aligned}  </fr:tex>
</fr:mainmatter></fr:tree>
 
