expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2336</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Example</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00L1</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00L1.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Examples of <fr:link
href="jms-00L0.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00L0">isomorphic sets</fr:link></fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>23</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author><fr:contributor><fr:link
href="marcelofiore.xml"
type="local"
addr="marcelofiore">Marcelo Fiore</fr:link></fr:contributor></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>A <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KR">bijection</fr:link> between finite sets is just a “relabeling” of its elements: for example, we have <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left \{ 0,1 \right \} \mathclose {}} \cong { \mathopen {} \left \{ \mathsf {false} , \mathsf {true} \right \} \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>. Isomorphism of infinite sets can be more confusing: for example, we have <fr:tex>\mathbb {N} \cong { \mathopen {} \left \{ n: \mathbb {N} \, \middle \vert \, n&gt;0 \right \} \mathclose {}}</fr:tex>, <fr:tex>\mathbb {N} \cong \mathbb {Z}</fr:tex>, <fr:tex>\mathbb {N} \cong \mathbb {N} \times \mathbb {N}</fr:tex>, <fr:tex>\mathbb {N} \cong \mathbb {Q}</fr:tex>, and even <fr:tex>{ \mathopen {} \left ( \mathbb {N} \to \mathbb {N} \right ) \mathclose {}} \cong \mathbb {R}</fr:tex>.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree><fr:tree
xmlns:fr="http://www.jonmsterling.com/jms-005P.xml"
toc="true"
numbered="true"
show-heading="true"
show-metadata="false"
expanded="true"
root="false"><fr:frontmatter><fr:anchor>2339</fr:anchor><fr:taxon>Remark</fr:taxon><fr:addr>jms-00L2</fr:addr><fr:route>jms-00L2.xml</fr:route><fr:title>Which <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KR">bijection</fr:link>?</fr:title><fr:date><fr:year>2024</fr:year><fr:month>1</fr:month><fr:day>23</fr:day></fr:date><fr:authors><fr:author><fr:link
href="jonmsterling.xml"
type="local"
addr="jonmsterling">Jon Sterling</fr:link></fr:author></fr:authors></fr:frontmatter><fr:mainmatter><fr:p>Although we are speaking of “being isomorphic” as the property of there being a <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KR">bijection</fr:link> between them, in practice, it is almost <fr:em>never</fr:em> useful to know that there exists some undetermined <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KR">bijection</fr:link> between given sets; it is always important to know <fr:em>which</fr:em> <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KR">bijection</fr:link>. Indeed, we have seen in <fr:ref
addr="jms-00KT"
href="jms-00KT.xml"
taxon="Proposition"></fr:ref> that there can be many distinct <fr:link
href="jms-00KR.xml"
type="local"
addr="jms-00KR">bijections</fr:link> between two sets.</fr:p></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:mainmatter></fr:tree></fr:context><fr:related><fr:tree
